Black-box Stealthy GPS Attacks on Unmanned Aerial Vehicles

Amir Khazraei, Haocheng Meng, and Miroslav Pajic The authors are with the Department of Electrical & Computer Engineering, Duke University, Durham, NC 27708. Email: {amir.khazraei, haocheng.meng, miroslav.pajic}@duke.edu.This work is sponsored in part by the ONR under agreement N00014-23-1-2206, AFOSR under the award number FA9550-19-1-0169, and by the NSF CNS-1652544 award and the National AI Institute for Edge Computing Leveraging Next Generation Wireless Networks, Grant CNS-2112562.
Abstract

This work focuses on analyzing the vulnerability of unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) to stealthy black-box false data injection attacks on GPS measurements. We assume that the quadcopter is equipped with IMU and GPS sensors, and an arbitrary sensor fusion and controller are used to estimate and regulate the system’s states, respectively. We consider the notion of stealthiness in the most general form, where the attack is defined to be stealthy if it cannot be detected by any existing anomaly detector. Then, we show that if the closed-loop control system is incrementally exponentially stable, the attacker can cause arbitrarily large deviation in the position trajectory by compromising only the GPS measurements. We also show that to conduct such stealthy impact-full attack values, the attacker does not need to have access to the model of the system. Finally, we illustrate our results in a UAV case study.

I Introduction

Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs), specifically quadcopters, have become indispensable tools across various applications such as aerial photography, search and rescue, military, agriculture, surveying and inspection, package delivery, and many more. Despite the immense potential, ensuring security and safety of UAVs remains a significant challenge that requires considerable attention. A critical sensor that UAVs heavily rely on is Global Positioning System (GPS) sensor, used for both localization and the navigation tasks. However, GPS sensors are known to be vulnerable to jamming and spoofing attacks [1]. Specifically, GPS spoofing provides control over the victim UAV without the need to compromise the flight control software; where the attacker only needs to be equipped with a radio-frequency transmitter.

In particular, numerous methods have been proposed to show the impact of GPS attacks on UAVs [2, 3, 4, 1]. There, the goal of the attacker has been to either deviate the drone’s trajectory [2], or take over the control of the drone by navigating it through a desired trajectory [3, 4, 1]. Since these methods have not considered stealthiness of the attacks, it has been shown that these attacks could be detected using either physics-based [5] or machine learning-based [6] anomaly detectors (AD). Hence, the moment an attack is detected, a recovery method and/or a safe planning/control algorithm could be applied to ensure safety (e.g., land the drone in a safe place). However, in case of a stealthy attack (i.e., that is undetectable by the AD), devising countermeasures becomes even more challenging as the usual initial step towards attack-resilience is attack detection.

The notion of attack stealthiness has been widely considered in attack-resilient control systems literature. For example, [7, 8, 9, 10, 11] study the impact of sensor attacks on linear time-invariant (LTI) control systems, aiming to cause large deviations in state estimates while remaining stealthy from a fixed AD. However, these works are limited to LTI systems and require the attacker to have access to the system model. Further, there is no guarantee that the attack will be stealthy against other types of ADs. Some recent works consider sensor attacks where stealthiness is independent of the deployed AD; i.e., the attack is stealthy if it is stealthy from any existing AD [12, 13]. For instance, [12] examines sensor attacks on scalar LTI systems, while [13] extends the results to LTI systems with general state dimensions. However, they assume the attacker has full access to the system model, and the duration of the stealthy attack is limited.

Since UAVs have nonlinear dynamical models, attacks relying on LTI models are less effective. Vulnerability of nonlinear control systems to stealthy sensor attacks, independent of the deployed AD, has been recently addressed [14, 15, 16]. It has been shown that if the attacker has access to the system states and model, and the system meets certain properties, it is vulnerable to stealthy impactful attacks.

This work aligns with prior research by considering sensor attacks on nonlinear control systems [14, 17, 15, 16, 18]. Yet, there are two main distinctions: the sensor attacks considered here are black-box, meaning the attacker does not need access to the system model or states, and we show that a stealthy, impactful attack can be launched solely by compromising the GPS sensor. We propose attack vectors that, by only compromising the GPS sensor, cause deviation in the drone’s trajectory while remaining stealthy from any existing AD. The contributions of this paper are twofold: our attack is black-box, not requiring access to the system model or states, and we provide conditions under which the attack remains stealthy from any AD. Specifically, we show if the closed-loop control system is incrementally stable, the attack will remain stealthy while deviating the UAV’s trajectory.

III-A2 Control Unit

The controller, shown in Figure 1, includes a sensor fusion module (state estimator), a feedback controller, and an anomaly detector (AD). Below, we provide details on the sensor fusion and feedback controller. The AD will be discussed after introducing the attack model.

Sensor Fusion

Accurate state estimation is essential for effective control of the UAV’s attitude and position. As IMU measurements do not directly measure 𝛀𝛀\mathbf{\Omega} and both the IMU and GPS are subject to noise, sensor fusion is necessary to estimate the states. Considering that the IMU has a higher sampling rate than the GPS (Ti​m​u<Tg​p​ssubscript𝑇𝑖𝑚𝑢subscript𝑇𝑔𝑝𝑠T_{imu}<T_{gps}), we update the state estimates based on the IMs sampling rate. In a general form, state estimates evolve using the dynamics

III-A3 Attack Model

We consider a sensor attack model targeting GPS measurements, where the information received by the controller differs from the actual measurements. Such attacks can be non-invasive (e.g., GPS spoofing [1]), or involve compromising the information flow between the GPS sensor and the controller (e.g., network-based attacks [25]). In either case, the attacker can ‘inject’ a desired false data into the current GPS sensor measurements. Thus, assuming the attack begins at time k=0𝑘0k=0, the compromised GPS measurements delivered to the controller can be modeled as [26]

𝐲k𝐩,c,a=𝐲k𝐩,a+ak,k∈ℤ≥0g;formulae-sequencesuperscriptsubscript𝐲𝑘𝐩𝑐𝑎superscriptsubscript𝐲𝑘𝐩𝑎subscript𝑎𝑘𝑘superscriptsubscriptℤabsent0𝑔\mathbf{y}_{k}^{\mathbf{p},c,a}=\mathbf{y}_{k}^{\mathbf{p},a}+a_{k},~{}~{}k\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}^{g}; (13)

Since the sensor fusion and controller use the compromised sensor data to compute state estimates 𝐱^tsubscript^𝐱𝑡\hat{\mathbf{x}}_{t} and input 𝐮tsubscript𝐮𝑡\mathbf{u}_{t}, the attack impacts the system’s evolution. We use the superscript a𝑎a to denote any signal from a compromised system, e.g., 𝐲k𝐩,asuperscriptsubscript𝐲𝑘𝐩𝑎\mathbf{y}_{k}^{\mathbf{p},a} for pre-attack measurements, and 𝐗a\ensurestackMath​\stackon​[1​p​t]=Δ[𝐱aT(𝐱^a)T𝒳𝒶T]T\ensurestackMath\stackondelimited-[]1𝑝𝑡Δsuperscript𝐗𝑎superscriptmatrixsuperscriptsuperscript𝐱𝑎𝑇superscriptsuperscript^𝐱𝑎𝑇superscriptsuperscript𝒳𝒶𝑇𝑇\mathbf{X}^{a}\mathrel{\ensurestackMath{\stackon[1pt]{=}{\scriptstyle\Delta}}}\begin{bmatrix}{\mathbf{x}^{a}}^{T}&\left(\hat{\mathbf{x}}^{a}\right)^{T}&{\mathpzc{X}^{a}}^{T}\end{bmatrix}^{T} for the closed-loop plant state under attack.

In this study, we assume that the attacker does not have access to the system model, sensor fusion, or controller dynamics – i.e., we consider black-box attacks. However, the attacker has computation power to compute suitable attack signals. The objective is to design an attack signal aksubscript𝑎𝑘a_{k}, k∈ℤ≥0𝑘subscriptℤabsent0k\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}, that remains stealthy – i.e., undetected by the AD – while causing deviations in the UAV trajectory. The formal definition of the attacker’s goal will be provided after introducing the AD and the notion of stealthiness.

IV Formalizing Stealthiness and Attack Goals

In this section, we capture the conditions for which an attack sequence is stealthy from any AD. Specifically, an attack is defined to be strictly stealthy if there exists no detector that can detect the attack better than a random guess detector; here, by better we assume that the probability of true detection is greater than the probability of false alarm. However, achieving such stealthiness may not always be feasible. Therefore, we introduce ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-stealthiness, which, as demonstrated later, can be achieved for GPS attacks. For a detailed discussion on attack stealthiness see [14].

Definition 2.

Consider the system from (12). An attack sequence, {a0,a1,…}subscript𝑎0subscript𝑎1…\{a_{0},a_{1},...\}, is strictly stealthy if there exists no detector for which ptT​D−ptF​A>0superscriptsubscript𝑝𝑡𝑇𝐷superscriptsubscript𝑝𝑡𝐹𝐴0p_{t}^{TD}-p_{t}^{FA}>0 holds, for any t≥0𝑡0t\geq 0. An attack is ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-stealthy if for a given ϵ>0italic-ϵ0\epsilon>0, there exists no detector such that ptT​D−ptF​A>ϵsuperscriptsubscript𝑝𝑡𝑇𝐷superscriptsubscript𝑝𝑡𝐹𝐴italic-ϵp_{t}^{TD}-p_{t}^{FA}>\epsilon holds, for any t≥0𝑡0t\geq 0.

The following Lemma uses Neyman-Pearson theorem to capture the condition for which the received sensor measurements satisfy the stealthiness condition from Definition 2.

IV-A Formalizing Attack Goal

As discussed, the attacker aims to degrade control performance by causing the position trajectory to deviate by at least α𝛼\alpha from the desired trajectory. Specifically, there exists a time k′superscript𝑘′k^{\prime} after the attack starts (k=0𝑘0k=0) such that ‖𝐩k′a−𝐩k′‖≥αnormsuperscriptsubscript𝐩superscript𝑘′𝑎subscript𝐩superscript𝑘′𝛼\|\mathbf{p}_{k^{\prime}}^{a}-\mathbf{p}_{k^{\prime}}\|\geq\alpha for some α>0𝛼0\alpha>0. Additionally, the attacker seeks to remain stealthy (i.e., undetected by the AD), as formalized below.

Definition 3.

An attack sequence {a0,a1,…}subscript𝑎0subscript𝑎1…\{a_{0},a_{1},...\} is referred to as (ϵ,α)italic-ϵ𝛼(\epsilon,\alpha)-successful if there exists k′∈ℤ≥0superscript𝑘′subscriptℤabsent0k^{\prime}\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0} such that ‖𝐩k′a−𝐩k′‖≥αnormsuperscriptsubscript𝐩superscript𝑘′𝑎subscript𝐩superscript𝑘′𝛼\|\mathbf{p}_{k^{\prime}}^{a}-\mathbf{p}_{k^{\prime}}\|\geq\alpha and the attack is ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-stealthy for all k∈ℤ≥0𝑘subscriptℤabsent0k\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}. If such sequence exists, the system is called (ϵ,α)italic-ϵ𝛼(\epsilon,\alpha)-attackable.

From (19), the attacker does not need the system model to generate attack sequences, launching a stealthy and impactful attack by compromising only the GPS sensor, and not the IMU. With all parameters on the right-hand side of the inequality (LABEL:eq:b_epsilon_1) being constants, stealthiness can be controlled by choosing smaller values for ‖C‖norm𝐶\|C\|, though this will prolong the time required for the attack to be α𝛼\alpha-effective. Thus, there is a trade-off between stealthiness and effectiveness time. The GPS spoofed signals, 𝐲kc,asuperscriptsubscript𝐲𝑘𝑐𝑎\mathbf{y}_{k}^{c,a}, follow the dynamics (24). As 𝐗kfsuperscriptsubscript𝐗𝑘𝑓\mathbf{X}_{k}^{f} closely matches the UAV trajectory without the attack, the spoofed GPS signals appear legitimate to the controller.

VI Simulation Results

We modeled quadcopter dynamics with disturbances such as drag forces on the torque and thrust, generating IMU and GPS signals with Matlab’s built-in functions. For sensor fusion, we use Matlab’s Navigation toolbox and a cascade PID controller for attitude and position control. The position controller’s output serves as the set-point for the attitude controller. We also implement two ADs: χ2superscript𝜒2\chi^{2} and CUSUM [28], with a false alarm threshold of pF​A=0.001superscript𝑝𝐹𝐴0.001p^{FA}=0.001.

We simulate a waypoint tracking task, where the drone navigates through four points forming a square in the X−Y𝑋𝑌X-Y plane: starting at (0,0,10​m)0010m(0,0,10\text{m}), moving to (100​m,0,20​m)100m020m(100\text{m},0,20\text{m}), (100​m,100​m,20​m)100m100m20m(100\text{m},100\text{m},20\text{m}), (0,100​m,10​m)0100m10m(0,100\text{m},10\text{m}), and returning to (0,0,10​m)0010m(0,0,10\text{m}). Using the attacks from (19) with ‖C‖=0.05norm𝐶0.05\|C\|=0.05, Fig. 2a shows the drone’s trajectory without attack (blue) and with attack (red). The attack causes the drone to deviate by 10​m10𝑚10m from its intended endpoint. The orange line represents the sensor fusion output, which aligns with the trajectory in the absence of attack, indicating the system would perceive normal operation. Fig. 2b and Fig. 2c show the alarm rate of CUSUM and χ2superscript𝜒2\chi^{2} ADs for both cases when the system is free of attack and when the GPS is compromised (the attack starts at time zero) – the average true detection rate closely matches the average false detection rate for both ADs, demonstrating the attack’s stealthiness.

VII Conclusion

In this work, we analyzed the vulnerability of UAV to black-box stealthy false data injections on GPS sensors. We defined stealthiness as an attack that remains undetected by any anomaly detector. We demonstrated that if the system is closed-loop incrementally stable, by only compromising the GPS sensors, stealthy attacks can cause arbitrarily large deviations in the drone’s position trajectories. Moreover, we established that the attacker does not need access to the system model or any state information to execute the attacks.
